---
title: Talking About Your Family
description: Describe your family members, talk about what they do, and ask others about theirs
level: beginner
time: 20 minutes
---

# Grammar: Possessive Adjectives

## Mi, Tu, Su

To talk about family, you need to say whose family member it is. Spanish uses short possessives that go before the noun — and they change for singular vs. plural.

mi mamá
  my mom

mis hermanos
  my siblings

tu papá
  your dad (informal)

tus hijos
  your kids

su esposa
  his/her/your (formal) wife

sus abuelos
  his/her/your (formal) grandparents

## Singular vs. Plural

The possessive matches the noun it modifies, not the owner. "Mi" becomes "mis" before a plural noun, regardless of whether there's one owner or many.

mi hermana → mis hermanas
  my sister → my sisters

tu primo → tus primos
  your cousin → your cousins

# Grammar: Ser vs. Tener for Describing Family

## Ser — Who They Are

Use "ser" to describe identity, personality, and relationships.

Mi mamá es maestra.
  My mom is a teacher.

Mi hermano es muy chistoso.
  My brother is really funny.

## Tener — What You Have

Use "tener" to say how many family members you have and their ages.

Tengo dos hermanas.
  I have two sisters.

Mi abuela tiene setenta años.
  My grandma is seventy years old.

# Vocabulary: Immediate Family

la familia
  family
  [lah fah-MEE-lee-ah]

la mamá
  mom
  [lah mah-MAH]

el papá
  dad
  [ehl pah-PAH]

los padres
  parents
  [lohs PAH-drehs]

el hermano / la hermana
  brother / sister
  [ehl ehr-MAH-noh / lah ehr-MAH-nah]

los hermanos
  siblings
  [lohs ehr-MAH-nohs]

el hijo / la hija
  son / daughter
  [ehl EE-hoh / lah EE-hah]

los hijos
  children (sons and daughters)
  [lohs EE-hohs]

el esposo / la esposa
  husband / wife
  [ehl ehs-POH-soh / lah ehs-POH-sah]

