# Vocabulary: Describing Family Members

mayor
  older
  [mah-YOHR]

menor
  younger
  [meh-NOHR]

el/la mayor
  the oldest (sibling)
  [ehl/lah mah-YOHR]

el/la menor
  the youngest (sibling)
  [ehl/lah meh-NOHR]

el/la de en medio
  the middle child
  [ehl/lah deh ehn MEH-dee-oh]

gemelo / gemela
  twin (m/f)
  [heh-MEH-loh / heh-MEH-lah]

# Vocabulary: Family Talk (Northern Mexico)

la jefa / el jefe
  mom / dad (slang — literally "the boss")
  [lah HEH-fah / ehl HEH-feh]

mi vieja / mi viejo
  my wife / my husband (casual, affectionate — not rude in this context)
  [mee bee-EH-hah / mee bee-EH-hoh]

mi carnalito / mi carnalita
  my little bro / my little sis (slang)
  [mee kahr-nah-LEE-toh / mee kahr-nah-LEE-tah]

el carnal / la carnala
  brother / sister (slang — close bond)
  [ehl kahr-NAHL / lah kahr-NAH-lah]

la raza
  the family / the crew / the people (informal, affectionate)
  [lah RRAH-sah]

la familia es primero
  family comes first (common saying)
  [lah fah-MEE-lee-ah ehs pree-MEH-roh]

# Phrases: Talking About Your Family

¿Tienes hijos?
  Do you have kids?
  [tee-EH-nehs EE-hohs]

¿Cuántos hijos tienes?
  How many kids do you have?
  [KWAHN-tohs EE-hohs tee-EH-nehs]

Tengo dos hijos.
  I have two kids.
  [TEHN-goh dohs EE-hohs]

No tengo hijos todavía.
  I don't have kids yet.
  [noh TEHN-goh EE-hohs toh-dah-BEE-ah]

¿A qué se dedica tu mamá?
  What does your mom do (for work)?
  [ah keh seh deh-DEE-kah too mah-MAH]

Mi papá trabaja en...
  My dad works at/in...
  [mee pah-PAH trah-BAH-hah ehn]

¿Cómo está tu familia?
  How's your family?
  [KOH-moh ehs-TAH too fah-MEE-lee-ah]

Todos bien, gracias a Dios.
  Everyone's good, thank God.
  [TOH-dohs bee-EHN, GRAH-see-ahs ah dee-OHS]

